ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: SAN CLEMENTE; CITY OKS $400,000 LAND PURCHASE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FRANK MESSINA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A $400,000 land purchase for a new animal control shelter and fire department 
training center was authorized by the City Council this week. 
</P>
<P>
 The 2.4-acre plot sits on the future site of an industrial park, near Avenida 
Pico and Avenida La Pata. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition to the purchase price, the city agreed to give about $160,000 in 
sewer credits to the landowner, Rancho San Clemente Associates. 
</P>
<P>
 In San Clemente, developers receive allotments for sewer use from City Hall. 
Landowners who use more than their allotted share are charged extra.  
</P>
<P>
 Councilman Thomas Lorch voted against the purchase, saying the city would pay 
too much for the land. 
</P>
<P>
 Lorch said that with so many acres of open space available, "there could be 
some alternatives. I don't think this is such a good deal." 
</P>
<P>
 City officials said the property would cost about $4.50 per square foot. 
</P>
<P>
 Some land in the proposed industrial park costs as much as $8.94 per square 
foot, said interim Fire Chief Gene Begnell. 
</P>
<P>
 "This land is by no means a bad deal," he said. FRANK MESSINA 
</P>
</TEXT>
