<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: FOUNTAIN VALLEY; CITY OKS PAYING STATE $85,000 SETTLEMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DEBRA CANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council has approved a settlement of a lawsuit filed by state labor 
officials, who accused the city of failing to withhold $200,000 from a 
contractor who allegedly did not pay workers "prevailing" wages to build a 
library. 
</P>
<P>
 Under the terms of the settlement, approved by the council Tuesday in closed 
session, the city will pay the state $85,000 -- money the city withheld from 
the contractor's final payment because construction on the library was 
completed a year late, said City Atty. Alan R. Burns. 
</P>
<P>
 Labor commissioner Victoria Bradshaw of the state Industrial Relations 
Department notified City Manager Ray Kromer in June of 1991 to withhold the 
$200,000 after the state accused Rainey Construction Inc. of La Habra of not 
paying prevailing wages to construction workers on the library project. 
</P>
<P>
 A "prevailing" wage is defined as the minimum pay rate set by the state for 
public works projects. 
</P>
<P>
 But when the $2-million library was completed in June, 1991, the city paid 
Rainey for the project and accepted a $200,000 bond from the contractor to 
cover the state's claim. 
</P>
<P>
 "The state notified us late and didn't give us full notification," Kromer 
said. "By the time they notified us, we had already released money to finalize 
the contract." 
</P>
<P>
 An attorney representing the state labor commissioner could not be reached for 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
 The labor commissioner sued the city last November, contending that the city 
should not have accepted the bond and demanding the $200,000, Burns said. 
</P>
<P>
 Under the settlement, the city will allow the state to sue the bonding company 
and collect the $200,000. If the state collects on the full amount, Burns said, 
the city will be reimbursed for the $85,000. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think that we're very optimistic that the city is going to recoup the 
$85,000," Kromer said. "With that bond, we have hopefully covered the city." 
</P>
<P>
 As a result of disputes over the library construction, other lawsuits 
involving the city, the contractor and the architect are pending, Burns said. 
DEBRA CANO 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
