<HEADLINE>
<P>
UCI STUDENT WINS PRESTIGIOUS TRUMAN SCHOLARSHIP OF $30,000; ACADEMIA: THE 
ENGLISH AND COMPARATIVE LITERATURE SCHOLAR IS SCHOOL'S SECOND AWARD WINNER IN 2 
YEARS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALICIA DI RADO, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Julia Kiely already met one challenge when she returned to college to get her 
bachelor's degree more than a decade after graduating from a community college. 
</P>
<P>
 Now the 36-year-old UC Irvine undergraduate student has reached another 
milestone -- a prestigious Truman scholarship. 
</P>
<P>
 Kiely, an English and comparative literature scholar, is the second UCI 
student in two years to win the $30,000 scholarship. 
</P>
<P>
 Kiely said she will use the scholarship to pursue a master's degree in public 
policy and pay for her final undergraduate year at UCI. 
</P>
<P>
 "Politics is my life," said Kiely, a staunch Republican whose father was 
president of his college's Young Democrats club and whose mother headed her 
college's Young Republicans group. 
</P>
<P>
 Kiely graduated from Cerritos College in 1979 and took night classes in the 
succeeding years while working, she said. Kiely joined the staff of a local 
congressman, later became the director of government affairs with the Anaheim 
Chamber of Commerce and also worked as an organizer for oil industry interests, 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
 She was one of the founders of CAST -- or Child Abuse Service Team -- a group 
coordinating city, county and state agencies to make services to abused 
children less traumatic. 
</P>
<P>
 In 1992, after she was unable to find a job in government or politics, Kiely 
decided to get a bachelor's degree at UCI to compete in the job market. 
</P>
<P>
 Eventually, she said, she wants to serve as director or staff member of a 
foundation that supports and gives scholarships to abused children or youths at 
risk of falling into crime. 
</P>
<P>
 Kiely is pleased to have won the scholarship competing against younger 
students. 
</P>
<P>
 "I was much older" than the rest of them, Kiely said. "I could've been the 
mother of a couple of them." 
</P>
</TEXT>
