<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING BRIEFING: HE MUST HAVE BEEN DREAMING ABOUT A BAD DAY ON THE COURSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By --MAL FLORENCE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 From Jeff Rude of the Dallas Morning News: "Masters lore extends to the Crow's 
Nest, the loft above the clubhouse, where amateur contestants can stay.  
</P>
<P>
 "Tom Watson and Lanny Wadkins stayed there when they were both collegians in 
1970--and it was a memorable experience for Wadkins. 
</P>
<P>
 " 'Tom was screaming in his sleep every night,' " Wadkins said. " 'He had 
these blood-curdling yells. I don't know what he was on at Stanford, but it 
wasn't the same stuff I was on at Wake Forest.' " 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Trivia time: What is the highest score recorded on any hole in the Masters 
tournament? 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Watery grave: The par-five 15th hole was a nightmare for several players in 
Thursday's opening round of the Masters. 
</P>
<P>
 Nolan Henke found the water fronting the hole and got a 10; Payne Stewart had 
a nine and Tom Watson an eight, among other soaring scores. 
</P>
<P>
 However, they didn't break the record for futility on No. 15. That still 
belongs to Jumbo Ozaki, who got an 11 during the 1987 Masters. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Slight omission: Barry Switzer, known for his rapport with players while 
coaching at Oklahoma, was criticized for being too lax. But as he said later: 
</P>
<P>
 "It never occurred to me to put up a sign in the dorm saying, 'It is against 
team rules to commit a felony.' " 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Organ boy: Dusty Hoffman, 12, has this dream. He wants to play for the 
Cincinnati Reds. Play the organ, that is. 
</P>
<P>
 For now, he's playing the organ at the home games of the Rapid City (S.D.) 
Thrillers of the Continental Basketball Assn. 
</P>
<P>
 Although Thriller officials were concerned about his age, they gave him the 
job because they wanted someone who would stick around. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Stunned: Was Dallas Cowboy cornerback Larry Brown surprised by Coach Jimmy 
Johnson's departure? 
</P>
<P>
 "It's like having a baby and not even knowing your wife was pregnant," he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Class-A New York: David Letterman, on Michael Jordan being reassigned by the 
Chicago White Sox to their double-A team in Birmingham, Ala.:  
</P>
<P>
 "For those of you who don't follow baseball, that's two levels below their 
major league team--and one level above the Mets." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Choirboys? Bruce Schoenfeld of the Sporting News reported that Utah Jazz 
officials are concerned about the character of the players who represent the 
NBA franchise: 
</P>
<P>
 "When the Jazz were considering drafting (Karl) Malone out of Louisiana Tech, 
they went so far as to ask his kindergarten teacher what kind of person he 
was." 
</P>
<P>
 Jazz President Frank Layden said: "I think we've sacrificed a chance at the 
championship more than once by not picking up some of the jerks who have passed 
through the league and could play." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Runner-up again: From columnist Scott Ostler of the San Francisco Chronicle:  
</P>
<P>
 "Bill Clinton threw out the first ball in Cleveland and Nancy Kerrigan threw 
out the first ball in Boston, and Nancy had to settle for the silver medal 
because the judges felt Clinton had a better program, and better stuff." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Trivia answer: Tom Weiskopf and Tommy Nakajima each scored a 13 on the 
par-three 12th and par-five 13th holes, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Quotebook: Indiana basketball Coach Bob Knight: "If the NBA was on Channel 5 
and a bunch of frogs making love were on Channel 4, I'd watch the frogs, even 
if they were coming in fuzzy." --MAL FLORENCE 
</P>
