<HEADLINE>
<P>
BASEBALL / DAILY REPORT; ANGELS; JACKSON HEATS UP TALK IN THE CLUBHOUSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB NIGHTENGALE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Angels were spending most of their time in the clubhouse before the game 
talking about the frigid weather in Milwaukee, putting on long johns, and 
planning on how they would keep warm. 
</P>
<P>
 Bo Jackson suddenly brought the conversation to a halt. 
</P>
<P>
 "I wish you guys will quit worrying about the weather," he yelled. "I didn't 
come all the way here to lose." 
</P>
<P>
 Actually, the weather was not nearly as bad as forecast, with the game-time 
temperature announced at 48 degrees. The Angels, however, swore it dropped 
dramatically by the game's conclusion. 
</P>
<P>
 "They tell you it's psychological," second baseman Harold Reynolds said, "and 
pretend like you're in Hawaii. But as soon as you breathe outside, and can see 
your breath, you tell yourself, 'Hey, this ain't no Hawaii.' " 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Pitcher Mark Leiter wants to help those families whose children are suffering 
from terminal diseases, which is why he established the non-profit Ryan Leiter 
Fund in memory of his son. 
</P>
<P>
 "The biggest shame of the whole thing," Leiter said, "would be not do anything 
to let people know about it. 
</P>
<P>
 "I didn't want to look back and say, 'Here I am a ballplayer, and you have all 
the media around, and I didn't do anything in Ryan's name to hopefully some day 
come up with a cure for this.' " BOB NIGHTENGALE 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA040994-0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 030624 </DOCID>
