<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: SIMI VALLEY; LANDOWNERS AGAIN OFFER CITY PARCELS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SARA CATANIA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 For the second time in four months, a group of Simi Valley landowners with 
property zoned for a regional mall are offering to sell two neighboring parcels 
to the city. 
</P>
<P>
 Rick Lagomarsino, Robert Eadington and Bub and Kathleen Orton are scheduled to 
meet in closed session with the City Council on Monday to discuss the price of 
the property. 
</P>
<P>
 In December, Gary Seaton of Mitchell Realtors, representing the landowners, 
offered to sell the city the 80 acres of undeveloped land for about $8.8 
million -- about the same per-square-foot price the city paid a month earlier 
for 32 acres nearby. 
</P>
<P>
 But City Manager Lin Koester rejected the offer, saying the city had achieved 
its goal of owning a key piece of mall land with the 32-acre purchase. 
</P>
<P>
 The amount being requested by the landowners this time is being kept 
confidential until negotiations are completed. 
</P>
<P>
 In mid-December the city agreed to pay $3.5 million for the 32-acre parcel, 
hoping they could use it to lure a mall developer to the city. SARA CATANIA 
</P>
</TEXT>
