<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: PLACENTIA; COUNCILMAN TO SERVE ON BASE REUSE PANEL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DANIELLE A. FOUQUETTE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council this week decided to send Councilman Michael L. Maertzweiler 
as its representative to the El Toro Reuse Planning Authority Executive 
Council. 
</P>
<P>
 Orange County Supervisor Thomas F. Riley asked the city to appoint a council 
member to the Executive Council, which will serve as an advisory board to the 
nine members of the planning authority. 
</P>
<P>
 Mayor Norman Z. Eckenrode and several other council members had expressed 
concern about the voting structure, which gives the five supervisors, three 
representatives from Irvine and one from Lake Forest each one vote. 
</P>
<P>
 Members of the Executive Council will not vote on how the El Toro Marine Corps 
Air Station is to be used when the military moves out in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
 Being on the Executive Council "gives us a voice, but does it give us a vote?" 
Councilwoman Carol Downey asked. 
</P>
<P>
 City Administrator Robert D'Amato said by sending a representative, the city 
would have a vote on what the executive council recommends to the planning 
authority, but that vote would not be binding. DANIELLE A. FOUQUETTE 
</P>
</TEXT>
